<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>heavy in hand • heavy-handed</xh5><p> <i>heavy in hand</i>—(of people, horses, etc.) hard to manage or control: Even if Jane was a little <u>heavy in hand</u>, with that appearance it didn’t so very much matter.</p><p><i>heavy-handed—</i>1. awkward in the use of hands: She even taught <u>heavy-handed</u> but dauntless colliers, who were seized with passion to “play.” 2. inclined to severe punishment: Grandfather was <u>heavy-handed</u> with his own children but very indulgent with us grandchildren. 3. <i>(of an approach, methods, etc.)</i> harsh: Regulation of the electricity market started in a light-handed fashion but there has been an increasing trend towards more <u>heavy-handed</u> regulation. 4. <i>(of a joke, style, etc.)</i> inept or clumsy; lacking lightness or grace: Their jokes are very <u>heavy-handed</u>, and generally involve discomfort for the victim.</p><p> <i>See also: have a heavy hand / have a light hand.</i></p> </entry>
